{{legend|#FF0000|Unofficial Romance language}}]]
[[File:Map-Romance Language World.png|thumb|350px| Global distribution of ''[[Romance languages]]'':<br>'''<span style="color:blue;">Blue</span>''' – [[French language|French]]; '''<span style="color:#00B927;">Green</span>''' – [[Spanish language|Spanish]]; '''<span style="color:#FF8400;">Orange</span>''' – [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]; '''<span style="color:#cccc00;">Yellow</span>''' – [[Italian language|Italian]]; '''<span style="color:red;">Red</span>''' – [[Romanian language|Romanian]]]]

The '''legacy of the Roman Empire''' has been varied and significant, comparable to that of other [[hegemony|hegemonic]] [[polity|polities]] of world history (e.g. [[Persian Empire]], [[ancient Egypt]] or [[imperial China]]).

The [[Roman Empire]] itself, built upon the legacy of other cultures such as [[Ancient Greece]], has had long-lasting influence with broad geographical reach on a great range of cultural aspects, including state institutions, [[civil law (legal system)|law]], cultural values, religious beliefs, technological advances, engineering and language.

This legacy survived [[Fall of the Western Roman Empire|the demise]] of the empire itself (5th century AD in the West, and [[Fall of Constantinople|15th century AD]] in the [[Eastern Roman Empire|East]]) and went on to shape other civilisations, a process which continues to this day. The city of [[Rome]] was the ''civitas'' (reflected in the etymology of the word "[[civilisation]]") and connected with the actual [[western civilisation]] on which subsequent cultures built.

One main legacy is the [[Latin]] language of ancient Rome, epitomized by the [[Classical Latin]] used in [[Latin literature]], [[historical linguistics|evolved]] during the [[Middle Ages]] and remains in use in the [[Roman Catholic Church]] as [[Ecclesiastical Latin]]. [[Vulgar Latin]], the common tongue used for regular social interactions, evolved simultaneously into the various [[Romance languages]] that exist today (notably [[Italian language|Italian]], [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], etc.). Although the [[Western Roman Empire]] fell in the 5th century AD, the [[Eastern Roman Empire]] continued until its conquest by the [[Ottoman Empire]] in the 15th century AD and cemented the [[Greek language]] in many parts of the [[Eastern Mediterranean]] even after the [[Early Muslim conquests]] of the 7th century AD. Although there has been a small modern revival of the [[Hellenistic religion]] with [[Hellenism (religion)|Hellenism]], ancient [[Religion in ancient Rome|Roman paganism]] was largely [[Early Christianity|displaced by Roman Catholic Christianity]] after the 4th century AD and [[Constantine the Great and Christianity|the Christian conversion]] of [[Roman emperor]] [[Constantine the Great|Constantine I]] (r. 306-337 AD). The Christian faith of the late Roman Empire continued to evolve [[History of Christianity during the Middle Ages|during the Middle Ages]] and remains a major facet of [[History of modern Christianity|the religion]] and the psyche of the modern [[Western world]].

[[Ancient Roman architecture]], largely indebted to [[ancient Greek architecture]] of the [[Hellenistic period]], has influenced the [[Classical architecture|architecture of the Western world]], particularly during the [[Italian Renaissance]] of the 15th century. [[Roman law]] and [[republic]]an politics (from the age of the [[Roman Republic]]) have left an enduring legacy, influencing the [[Maritime republics|Italian city-state republics]] of the Medieval period as well as the early [[United States]] and other modern [[democratic republic]]s. The [[Julian calendar]] of ancient Rome formed the basis of the standard modern [[Gregorian calendar]], while [[Roman technology|Roman inventions]] and engineering, such as the construction of [[concrete]] [[dome]]s, continued to influence various peoples after the fall of Rome. Roman models of [[colonialism]] and of warfare also became influential.

== Language ==
{{Main|Romance languages|Romance-speaking world}}

[[Latin]] became the [[lingua franca]] of the early Roman Empire and later of the [[Western Roman Empire]], while - particularly in the [[Eastern Roman Empire]] - indigenous languages such as [[Greek language|Greek]] and to a lesser degree [[Egyptian language| Egyptian]] and [[Aramaic| Aramaic language]] continued in use. Despite the decline of the Western Roman Empire, the Latin language continued to flourish in the very different social and economic environment of the [[Middle Ages]], not least because it became the official language of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. [[Koine Greek]], which served as a lingua franca in the Eastern Empire, remains in use today as a [[Sacred language#Christianity|sacred language]] in some [[Eastern Orthodox Church | Eastern Orthodox churches]].

In [[Western Europe| Western]] and [[Central Europe]] and in parts of northern [[Africa]], Latin retained its elevated status as the main vehicle of communication for the learned classes throughout the [[Middle Ages]] and subsequently; witness especially the [[Renaissance]] and [[Baroque]] periods. Books which had a revolutionary impact on science, such as [[Nicolaus Copernicus]]' ''[[De revolutionibus orbium coelestium]]'' (1543), were composed in Latin. This language was not supplanted for scientific purposes until the 18th century, and for formal descriptions in [[zoology]], as well as [[botany]] - it survived to the later 20th century.<ref>See [[History of Latin]].</ref> The modern international [[binomial nomenclature]] holds to this day: taxonomists assign a [[Scientific name| Latin or Latinized name]] as the scientific name of each [[species]].

In the 21st century the [[Romance languages]], which comprise all languages that descended from [[Latin]], are spoken by more than 920 million people as their [[first language | mother tongue]], and by 300 million people as a [[second language]], mainly in the Americas, Europe, and Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.britannica.com/topic/Romance-languages |title= Romance languages |publisher= Britannica.com |date= |accessdate= 2018-11-24}}</ref> Romance languages are either [[official language | official]], co-official, or significantly used in 72 countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://departamento.pucp.edu.pe/educacion/areas-academicas/curriculo-y-didactica/curriculo-y-didactica-publicaciones/language-acquisition-romance-speaking-world-peru/ |title= Language Acquisition in the Romance Speaking World: Peru - Departamento de Educación |publisher= Departamento.pucp.edu.pe | date= |accessdate= 2016-05-14}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=June 2020}}<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=zM_mBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=%22romance+speaking+world%22#v=onepage&q=%22romance%20speaking%20world%22&f=false |title= Manual of Language Acquisition - Google Libros |date= 2014-08-25 |accessdate= 2016-05-14|isbn= 9783110302257 |last1= Fäcke |first1= Christiane }}</ref>{{qn|date=June 2020}}<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=eOUfbeTC-tsC&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=romanophone+world#v=onepage&q=romanophone%20world&f=false |title= Multilingualism, Education and Change - Jean Jacques Weber - Google Libros |accessdate= 2016-05-14|isbn= 9783631572856 |last1= Weber |first1= Jean Jacques |year= 2009 }}</ref>{{qn|date=June 2020}}<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=_ZmZ21jOH9EC&pg=RA1-PT73&lpg=RA1-PT73&dq=romanophone+world#v=onepage&q=romanophone%20world&f=false |title= Language in the Media: Representations, Identities, Ideologies - Google Libros |date= 2007-09-19 |accessdate= 2016-05-14|isbn= 9781441151254 |last1= Johnson |first1= Sally |last2= Ensslin |first2= Astrid }}</ref>{{qn|date=June 2020}}<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=hprLhm1Xra0C&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=%22neolatin+world%22#v=onepage&q=%22neolatin%20world%22&f=false |title= I nomi dei fiumi, dei monti, dei siti: strutture linguistiche preistoriche - Claudio Beretta - Google Libros |accessdate= 2016-05-14|isbn= 9788820330989 |last1= Beretta |first1= Claudio |year= 2003 }}</ref>{{qn|date=June 2020}}<ref>{{cite journal|author= USA |title= Radiation oncology in Latin speaking countries: A link between Europe and Latin America. |date= 2015-09-28 |pmid= 25061515 |doi= 10.1016/j.rpor.2013.06.004 |volume= 19 |pmc=4104016 |journal= Rep Pract Oncol Radiother |issue= 4 |pages= 227–9}}</ref>{{qn|date=June 2020}} Of the [[United Nations]]' six [[Official languages of the United Nations | official languages]], two (French and Spanish) descend from Latin.

Additionally, Latin has had a great influence on both the grammar{{cn|date=June 2020}} and the lexicon of [[West Germanic languages]]. Romance words make respectively 59%, 20% and 14% of [[English language |English]], [[German language |German]] and [[Dutch language |Dutch]] vocabularies.<ref>{{cite book |last= Finkenstaedt |first= Thomas |author2= Dieter Wolff  |title= Ordered Profusion; studies in dictionaries and the English lexicon |publisher= C. Winter |year= 1973 |isbn=3-533-02253-6}}</ref><ref>Uwe Pörksen, German Academy for Language and Literature's Jahrbuch [Yearbook] 2007 (Wallstein Verlag, Göttingen 2008, pp. 121-130)</ref><ref name="Walter">{{cite book|url= https://pure.knaw.nl/ws/files/475024/Van_der_Sijs_Loanwords_in_the_World's_Languages.pdf|title= Loanwords in the World's Languages: A Comparative Handbook |page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=HnKeVbwTwyYC&lpg=PP1&hl=en&pg=PA370#v=onepage&q&f=false 370] |publisher= Walter de Gruyter |year= 2009}}</ref> Those figures can rise dramatically when only non-compound and non-derived words are included. Accordingly, Romance words make roughly 35% of the vocabulary of Dutch.<ref name=Walter/> Of all the loanwords in Dutch, 32.2% come directly from some form of Latin (excluding loans from Romance languages).<ref>
